snippet.textDisplay:
Wild analysis. Wilder is nearly unbeatable in a straight, fair fight which his first encounter with Fury had shown. This time as the rounds progressed [ U hv to hv the full fight for reference ] Fury settled on a historical little trick : just grab Wilders' head down and beat his blood out. The referee though warned Fury, u never know the equations in the background; later, he starts taking a distance and acting late. This is the trick that worked well against that unputdownable Mike Tyson effectively organized by Evander Holyfield, Lennox Lewis and finally by Peter Mcneeley. See the full fights to check the truth. Just don't give Mike or Willder the space to box and injure him by body & face punching, headbutting whatever--while holding him down. Rest will follow. This merits sheer disqualification but boxing has queer rules, the judges or the referee don't object to, or penalize, when it becomes one with wrestling. This is foul play of the most acceptable kind; or politics and its intervals for intrigue to be made.
I see that this has been endorsed by Wilder himself in his statement against the referee which follows :
“Bayless had come in my dressing room, looked me in my eyes and said if I hit Fury in the back of the head – rabbit punch – or hit off of the break, he would disqualify me or deduct two points from me. I guess those rules just applied to me because they didn’t apply to my opponent. (Fury) hit me in the back of the neck and the head all night and Bayless didn’t do anything about it, to the point I got lumps and bruises. That was a thing that was very frustrating to me.”

He continued to say about Bayless deducting a point from Fury in the fifth round:

“Why are you taking a point now when he’s been doing this all through the fight?” Wilder said he roared to Bayless. “What happened to that speech? What happened to that disqualification? All those things you said you’d do to me?”
[ https://ftw.usatoday.com/2020/02/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-referee-kenny-bayless-blamed-excuses-boxing ]
Like Tyson, Wilder enters history like a Hero, defeated by con men and their dirty tricks, and not boxing.
